# Portfolio Project Standards

## Stack and style
- Use TypeScript for all app logic and React functional components.
- Keep components and pages simple, readable, and focused on one responsibility.
- Prefer existing project patterns before introducing new abstractions.

## UI and layout
- Maintain the existing clean, minimal portfolio style unless explicitly asked to redesign.
- Prefer Ant Design components where possible instead of pure HTML tags.
- Keep semantic HTML structure and accessible labels, headings, and link text.
- Ensure responsive behavior for mobile and desktop when changing layout.

## Component structure
- Each component must be in its own folder named after the component.
- The component entry file must be `index.tsx`.
- Keep styles in a `styles.module.css` file.
- Keep constants in a `consts` file.
- Keep helpers in a `utils` file.
- Keep component types in a `types` file.
- Declare components as named exports using arrow functions.
- Type component props explicitly (no implicit `any` props).

### Component grouping by usage
- Group all components by usage inside `src/components/`.
- Use `src/components/_shared/` for reusable generic components (for example `Button`, `Input`, `Modal`).
- Use `src/components/layout/` for layout structure components (for example `Header`, `Footer`, `Sidebar`, `Main`).
- Use `src/components/features/` for feature-specific components (for example `PostCard`, `UserList`).
- Do not mix categories: each component must live in exactly one of these folders.

### Component declaration style

```tsx
import type { ButtonProps } from './types';

export const Button = (props: ButtonProps) => {
  return <button>{props.children}</button>;
};
```

### Expected component layout

```text
MyComponent/
  index.tsx
  styles.module.css
  consts.ts
  utils.ts
  types.ts
```

## Pages as composition layers
- Pages must act as composition and orchestration layers only.

### Page structure
- Each page must be in its own folder inside `src/pages/`, named after the page.
- The entry file must be `index.tsx`.
- Add `consts.ts`, `utils.ts`, and `types.ts` only when needed.

```text
pages/
  PageName/
    index.tsx
    styles.module.css
    consts.ts
    utils.ts
    types.ts
```

### Page rules
- Build pages by composing components only.
- Do not implement UI directly in pages (no raw HTML or UI library components).
- Move all UI, markup, and styles into components.
- Pages should handle data flow, state, and layout composition only.
- Keep pages clean, minimal, and free of complex JSX.
- Declare pages as named exports using arrow functions.
- Type props explicitly (no `any`).

## Routing structure
- All routing logic must be placed inside `src/router/`.
- Do not define routes inside `App.tsx` or inside page components.
- Use a dedicated `routes.ts` file for route configuration.
- Use `index.tsx` for router setup and router provider wiring.
- Use lazy loading for route components via `React.lazy`.
- Wrap lazy-loaded routes with `Suspense` and provide a clear loading fallback.
- Keep one route object per page/feature and compose routes in `routes.ts`.
- Prefer route-level code splitting to reduce initial bundle size.
- Handle unknown routes with a dedicated `NotFound` route.

### Expected router files

```text
src/router/
  index.tsx
  routes.ts
```

## Code quality
- Favor small helper functions over repeated JSX or duplicated logic.
- Do not add dependencies unless they are clearly needed for the request.

## TypeScript and lint strictness
- Enforce strict TypeScript for all changes.
- Do not use `any`; prefer exact types or `unknown` with narrowing.
- Do not ignore type errors or add type-bypass workarounds.
- Do not use `eslint-disable` comments, including single-line and file-level variants.
- Fix lint and type issues properly instead of suppressing checks.

## Styling constraints
- Do not use inline styles in JSX (for example `style={{ ... }}`).
- Place styling in dedicated style files.
- Keep visual rules outside component render logic.

## Safety checks before finishing
- Run or suggest relevant checks for changed code (build, lint, or type-check).
- Keep edits scoped to the request; do not refactor unrelated parts.
- Preserve existing user content and routes unless the request says otherwise.
